The Iranian Air Force is on full alert. Iranian authorities cut off the Internet throughout the country.

94% of Ukrainians noted an increase in the price of medicines and essential goods over the past year.

This is highlighted in a survey conducted by the Rating sociological group at the end of November. It is notable that a similar survey of 2021, despite the relative peacetime, has shown almost the same number of people mentioned rising prices — 87%.

Ukrainians note a general decline in the country's economy — 83% believe that the economic situation has worsened over the past year. Negative changes also affected individual families. According to the survey, 63% of Ukrainians felt the deterioration of their family's financial situation, and 32% did not notice significant changes.

The economic crisis has greatly affected the labour market — 72% of respondents reported that it has become more difficult to find a job. At the same time, surveys of previous years show that the situation in the labour market continues to deteriorate for the fourth year in a row:

🔻 in 2019, Ukrainians rated the opportunity to find a job at 2.7 points out of 5; 
🔻 in 2021 — 2.3; 
🔻 in 2022 — 1.8.

In terms of age, the situation of young workers under 35 worsened the most. Last year's survey showed that it was increasingly difficult for aged Ukrainians to find a job. Now the younger generation has the greatest problems with employment.

Respondents age: 
🔻 from 18 to 35 years old rated the opportunity to find a job at 1.7 points (2.6 in 2021); 
🔻 from 36 to 50 — also 1.7 points (2.3 in 2021); 
🔻 from 50 — 1.9 (2.0 in 2021).

Among the positive changes, Ukrainians noted only the growth of defence capability (91%) and the improvement of the international image of Ukraine (89%).

The emblem of the SS division, 'Galicia', is not a Nazi symbol anymore

Recently, the Supreme Court of Ukraine decided that starting from December 5, 2022, the SS division 'Galicia' emblem is not recognized as Nazi on the territory of Ukraine. This was written by lawyer Vyacheslav Yakubenko, representing the Ukrainian Institute of National Memory in court. According to him, the decision of the Sixth Administrative Court of Appeal, dated September 23, 2020, remained in force, which stated that the emblem was not Nazi.

This decision was preceded by a long investigation launched in 2017 by the head of the Ukrainian Jewish Committee, Eduard Dolinsky, who demanded that the participants in the celebration of the 74th anniversary of the SS division 'Galicia' in Lviv be held accountable. Later, in September 2017, the head of the Sakcent Plus publishing house, Natalia Myasnikova, filed a lawsuit against Vladimir Vyatrovich, the then-head of the Institute of National Remembrance, for refusing to recognize the symbols as Nazi. In December 2019, Vyatrovich did not appear at the court hearing. In May 2020, the court invalidated Vyatrovich's answer about the symbols of the Galicia division.

Unfortunately, the rehabilitation of accomplices of Nazism and their 'heroes' continues in Ukraine.

The 14th SS Volunteer Infantry Division 'Galicia' was formed in 1943 as part of Nazi Germany's SS and participated in several military and punitive operations. Among other things:

▪️ fought against Soviet and Polish partisans in 1943-1944;
▪️ engagement in the 'pacification' of many villages in the south-east of Poland and Galicia in the same years;
▪️ in August-October 1944, they participated in the suppression of the Slovak National Uprising;
▪️ in January 1945, they were sent to fight against the Yugoslav partisans;
▪️until the very end of the war, they took an active part on the side of the troops of Nazi Germany in military operations against the Red Army.

As before, in peacetime, so during the war, the ruling capitalist class and its subordinate official representatives must hold fast to political dominance and economic power. It requires to use of any accessible means to divert the attention of the population from the root causes of the existing economic problems in the country, the consequence of which is the permanent impoverishment of the working class.

For the capitalist state, it is beneficial to finance various nationalist organizations that are the ideological followers of their rehabilitated 'glorious' predecessors, ready to smash any disagreement among the millions of working people of Ukraine or any other country but will never dare to bite the hand that feeds them.

What is the influence of oligarchs on the Ukrainian economy?

The Center for Economic Strategy of Ukraine published data that shows which sectors and regions of Ukraine were the most influenced by oligarchs before the outbreak of hostilities.

The most significant number of oligarchs were present in the raw materials, metallurgical, and energy sectors.

The complete list is following:

▪️Rinat Akhmetov — dominance in the production of coke, iron ores, and coal mining, electricity distribution, ferrous metallurgy;
▪️Viktor Pinchuk — in pipe production;
▪️Igor Kolomoisky — oil refining;
▪️Dmitry Firtash — the production of fertilizers and distribution of gas;
▪️Yuriy Kosyuk — a large production of eggs and chicken, concentrated in the Kyiv region;
▪️Pyotr Poroshenko — «agricultural confectioner,» Vinnytsia region;
▪️Viktor Pinchuk — Dnipropetrovsk region;
▪️Alexander Yaroslavsky — Dnipropetrovsk region;
▪️Sergey Tigipko — Dnipropetrovsk region;
▪️Sergey Taruta and Oleg Mkrtchan — ISD, Luhansk region;
▪️Rinat Akhmetov — Donetsk region;
▪️Igor Kolomoisky — Privat group, Poltava region;
▪️Konstantin Zhevago — Poltava region.

The share of oligarchs in the revenue of the country's economic sectors was distributed as follows (as of 2020):

▪️Coke production — 98%;
