A disappointing assessment of the damage inflicted on the population of Ukraine in the course of hostilities

We invite readers to familiarize themselves with the data from a survey of 2,000 people conducted by the Rating Sociological Group.

▪️32% of respondents said they suffered material losses as a result of the war,
▪️67% — did not suffer.

More than half of the inhabitants of the territories where hostilities were or are still ongoing suffered losses. Among the losses most often called:
▪️36% — money;
▪️23% — housing;
▪️14% — household appliances;
▪️7% — pets;
▪️6% — car;
▪️5% — production;
▪️4% — commercial real estate.

Every tenth respondent noted that his housing was either destroyed (2%) or damaged (8%). Another 5% do not know in what condition their housing is now. For 85%, the housing situation has stayed the same. About a third of those whose house is located on the hostilities territory noted that their housing was damaged. Also, one in five of those who have accommodation in the occupation zone do not know its condition.

According to the results, about a quarter of the respondents noted that they were forced to change their residence in Ukraine during the hostilities. Most of them are among those who lived in the war zone — 64% and in Kyiv — 42%. A third of those who left home have already returned. Also, 9% of the IDPs plan to return in the near future, and 15% will wait.

The main source of income for the majority of respondents is:
▪️56% — wages;
▪️31% — pension;
▪️8% — income from private business.

Regarding the amount of income itself:
▪️2% — increased;
▪️33% — has not changed;
▪️18% — slightly decreased;
▪️32% — significantly decreased;
▪️14% — lost almost everything.

Among those who had business as a source of income before the war, only 12% noted that it continues to work fully. Almost half mentioned that the company is operating but with lower income. On the other hand, 12% plan to close their business, and 28% no longer handle it. 30% of business income recipients had employees. Of these, almost 40% of employers had to fire employees, and more than 20% — had to reduce wages.

More than half of the respondents noted a deterioration in their physical health, and more than 60% — in their mental health. The deterioration of health is observed among residents of frontline zones and war zones, older people, less well-off people, and those who are separated from their families and lost relatives in the war.

47% noted that they have close relatives who served in the war. Almost 20% reported that they have among their close relatives those with whom they have lost contact and do not know where they are now. 5% — have relatives who died because of the war. 7% of respondents noted that personally or their close relatives were injured due to hostilities.

As for the prospects for restoring the infrastructure and economy of Ukraine, then:
▪️about 40% believe that five years will be enough;
▪️25% believe that up to ten years;
▪️23% — more than ten years;
▪️4% — will take less than a year.

Military expenditure during the war gobbles a massive part of the national income. The primary source of the unprecedented growth in the capitalists' profits at this time are state military orders at the expense of the federal budget, and the war only legitimizes widespread embezzlement. [1], [2], [3], [4], [5], [6]

Wars deepen the poverty of the working people, and the uneven and disproportionate development of the capitalist economy in wartime creates the conditions for new, even more, profound economic crises.

100 years ago, capitalist Russia had already experienced mobilization.

During the First World War, tsarist Russia was under incredible economic stress. Then, industrial and logistical underdevelopment, chaos and bureaucracy of management led to an extremely difficult situation in various areas of the country's economy.

Of course, one should not count on a repetition of such a crisis. However, the repetition of some of its features is quite likely. To «refresh» historical memory, let's see what Soviet historian P.V. Volobuyev wrote in his book «Economic Policy of the Provisional Government».
– a year after the start of WWI, an economic crisis began in Russia, gradually growing, affecting one industry branch after another;
– the backward economy was unable to withstand the severity of the «big war»;
– in 1916, about 80% of industrial workers worked for defense;
– the one-sided development of industry gave a temporary rise in heavy industries (metalworking, mechanical engineering, chemistry, etc.);
– but by the end of 1916, economic ruin had already become an obvious fact;
– the developing crisis contributed to the imperfection of the military economy organization in Russia in comparison with the Western countries;
– reactionary-bureaucratic regulation of economic life (the main means for weakening the destructive impact of the war on the economy) was organized in Russia in the worst possible way;
– in late 1916 — early 1917, the crisis took on the features of general devastation and an impending financial and economic catastrophe;
– railway transport was not able to ensure the transportation of a minimum of food cargo, fuel and raw materials;
– a drop in the export of fuel and raw materials — caused a decrease in coal production, a lack of coal and oil — the closure of factories, incomplete workload of enterprises;
– Rodzianko's report to Nicholas II a few days before the February Revolution: in St. Petersburg, out of 73 enterprises that stood in December 1916, 39 were closed due to a lack of fuel, 11 — due to a power outage caused by a lack of fuel at power plants;
– due to a lack of raw materials and fuel, the metallurgical industry rolled down;
– tension appeared with the food supply of the army and industrial centers;
– stocks of bread from the state bodies fell to a critical minimum: on March 1, 1917, there were only 20 million poods of them, with a monthly consumption rate of over 90 million poods.

ICU Financial Group has published a macroeconomic report on the situation in Ukraine

 Central annual forecasts (compared to 2021):

 ▫️ real GDP will fall by 32% by the end of the year (from $200 billion to $146 billion);
 ▫️ the unemployment rate will rise to 25%;
 ▫️ inflation will reach 29.5%;
 ▫️the hryvnia against the dollar will rise to 40.3;
 ▫️international reserves will amount to 23.3 billion dollars.  In 2021 they were 30.9 billion;
 ▫️public debt as a % of GDP will be 86%, compared to 49.7 in the control year;

 According to the report, in 2023, the situation will improve, but only slightly. GDP growth is forecast at 4%, and inflation at around 24%. At the same time:

 ▫️The exchange rate is expected to continue falling to UAH 45/USD 1;
 ▫️reserves will shrink to $19 billion;
 ▫️The debt will amount to a record 99% of GDP.

 As we can see, hostilities have cut substantially into the workers' standard of living.  At the same time, the capitalist government, which defended the interests of business, did nothing during the six months of the conflict to end this destructive chaos. The current situation shows again that apart from the workers, no one will defend their interests.

